            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "For me the issue is that\n\n```\ncall_atomic([['nvim_set_options_atomic', [\n    ['modifiable', 0],\n    ['readonly', 0]]],\n  ['nvim_buf_set_lines', ...]])\n```\n\nis kinda verbose. With special handles OTOH, the plugin would do once:\n\n`let my_handle = nvim_buf_get_owner_handle(buf)`\n\nand then can just do a normal `set_lines` etc calls. I don't suggest any involved \"ACLs/privilege management\" either. Just a single ownership/mutability flag is probably enough, and this would be associated purely with the handle, no keeping track of the identity of the plugin that owns the buffer or anything. For me the downside is more that the \"buffer number == buffer handle\" identity introduced by #4934 (so that object \"handles\" is purely an internal concept and users can just think in terms of vim buffer numbers/window ids) wouldn't be strictly true anymore.\n",
