        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> On the other hand, if this is not a common operatin, the verbosity of something like nvim_set_options_atomic seems justifiable and preferrable: rather than have some alternative universe of privileges (cognitive overhead), just offer this explicit sugar.\n\nIt seems we talk of two different things. I'm just saying that a plugin randomly modifying a buffer set `nomodifiable` by _someone else_ should be very uncommon and even an anti-pattern (it renders `nomodifiable` completely meaningless, a user doing a single edit is not different from the user asking a plugin to make  some single edit operation) . This is very different from a plugin exclusively modifying a buffer because it some sense owns the buffer (it created the buffer for a purpose or was given ownership by the user), for instance an append-only output buffer, like `out_io=buffer`, or a buffer implementing a \"user interface\" for a plugin, which is a pattern which I think we  should support in some way.\n\nAnd while a separate mutable handle might not _necessarily_ be the best way, I don't think the cognitive overhead of _something like that_ is in the scale of an \"alternative universe\".\n",
